User: Please write a Rust function that takes a u64 input and returns the largest prime number less than that value.
<response>fn largest_prime(n: u64) -> u64 {
    if n < 2 {
        return 0;
    }
    for i in (2..=(n - 1)).rev() {
        let mut is_prime = true;
        for j in 2..=(i as f64).sqrt() as u64 + 1 {
            if i % j == 0 {
                is_prime = false;
                break;
            }
        }
        if is_prime {
            return i;
        }
    }
    2
}

This function returns the largest prime number less than the input `n`. It does so by checking the primality of every number less than `n` starting from `n`. There are more efficient ways to compute primality, but here we check whether any number less than the square root of the candidate prime is a factor of that candidate.</response>
